name: Introduction to Probability and Data with R
reviews: It is an excellent introduction to probability and data. Concepts are explained really well, one of the best courses (not only among MOOCs). I think it would be improved by adding one week to the course dedicated to solely data analysis in R, as a precursor to the final project. There was too big of a gap in terms of R practice (for those new to R) between what was explained during the course and the final project. I would have found it super useful to have one more week in which to discuss how to treat missing data, how to clean data in R (even if just a simple cleaning, like getting rid of the NAs), followed by steps/do's and don'ts when analyzing data, different types of graphs in R appropriate for numerical and ordinal data, that sort of thing. That would have made it almost perfect.

name: Positive Psychology
institution: The University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill
reviews: At first, I imagined that it was only another scientific course, of those who are sold to the mountains over the internet and seek to teach you to seek only the positive side at all, simplifying dangerously the inherent complexity of human and life. But not. After completing it, I can talk quietly that I am convinced that this course is very serious and scientific. Moreover, in my view, he hits not to disregard the value of the duality of the sentimental plan of the human being (positive and negative emotions). His proposal is to awaken and develop in the student the ability to deal more fraternally with himself and with the other people around him in order to create, through good habits, a healthier community in all terms and aspects. In short, it is one more of the various "red pills" that we can take if we want to become more lucid and conscious about life.

name: Introduction to Classical Music
reviews: Very good course in general. I loved the prior analysis of what music is and then start with the history of music. The study until Romanticism was great, could have added Scarlatti, but not everything can be. If I think they could have divided romanticism into 2 stages, tall and under romanticism because what we got from Chopin, Liszt, Dvorak, Brahms and Rachmaninoff was disappointing. Not to mention the lack of Ravel and Shostakovich. Taking into account everything, it was a good course and I learned many things about classical music. It is also worth mentioning that Craig was a warm and entertaining host and made the most pleasant course to see.

name: Introduction to Classical Music
reviews: I really liked the course. I thought it makes a good introduction to theory of music and then to its history. It is a lot of information and at times it becomes difficult to remember all the concepts that have been explained, but it serves to have a first approach to the theme.

name: Children's Human Rights - An Interdisciplinary Introduction
reviews: At my opinion the course is well structured, the material is quite professional, complete and concise; In my case, as a litigant lawyer in the area of human rights of children and adolescence, she gave me several tools to take into consideration in my work. It was very useful and interesting to be able to listen and study this theme from the point of view of America, Europe, Africa and Asia mainly since it has a broader vision not only in the social area but legal. I would not like to let the opportunity happen to comment that it is clear that all the speakers have knowledge and experience in the subject, however, not all have the ease of transmitting them, I mainly refer to those who read their material (presentations, chips, etc. ) Which causes the attention to be lost because they only read but do not expose or explain. name: Data Visualization with Python
reviews: While the data visualization tools outlined here are valuable, the final assignment for this course does a very poor job of assessing the things that were actually taught.Early on, you are assured that the course will emphasize the scripting layer of matplotlib, rather than the more complex artist layer. In the final assignment, however, you are instructed to use the artist layer, and configure many parameters that were never covered in any of the labs or videos.Likewise, utilizing geojson files for choropleth maps was covered in the most cursory manner - you are never requried to open a geojson file, or understand how it is configured. You just load it in and carry on with the assignment. However, without understanding the setup of a geojson file, no student is going to understand how to properly configure the key_on parameter when making their own choropleth map for the final assignment.The ability to actually create a graph from a set of data is perhaps the smallest part of the final assessment. Everything else is fussing with irritating details, often details that we were never taught about in class.

name: Fundamentos de Finanzas Empresariales
reviews:
It is an excellent course at the introductory level, among other knowledge and skills that you can acquire when studying this course, are: to know and understand some of the most relevant financial indicators. Toilenciate between liquidity, operation, profitability and indebtedness indicators.
Identify the concept and applications of the value of money over time.
Identify the concept of interest, the application and calculation of equivalence of rates.
Learn the logic of the calculation and the concept of present value and future value, and calculate the payments of a debt.
Identify and apply different financial tools to do investment analysis.
Know and learn to calculate through Excel the net present value, the internal rate of return, the recovery period and the cost benefit ratio.
Calculate and interpret the WACC (capital cost) of a company or project.
Use the WACC as a discount rate for investment projects.
Evaluate different investment alternatives and choose the best according to the generated value.
Apply financial tools in Excel.

name: Biology Meets Programming: Bioinformatics for Beginners
reviews: It is a course that is fine to start in bioinformatics with Python. However, towards the middle of the course, the contents are too complex for those who have not worked previously in this field. It should be a little more basic so that it can be followed until the end and really learned. In addition, I believe that the biological problems that arise are too concrete. It would be nice to know, at a basic level, the usefulness of these tools in biology-biomedicine.

name: Biology Meets Programming: Bioinformatics for Beginners
reviews: This is billed as a course for beginners, but it leans heavily on one's prior skill in programming. If you're not familiar with Python syntax or you are a coding neophyte, a lot of the concepts will likely go over your head. The biology is fairly cursory and easy to pick up along the way, or simply ignore if you don't have a strong background in molecular biology/genetics.

name: Biology Meets Programming: Bioinformatics for Beginners
reviews: excellent introduction, which was at an appropriate level for my experience (lots of programming in languages other than python, and just a cursory understanding of genomics).

name: Mindshift: Break Through Obstacles to Learning and Discover Your Hidden Potential
reviews: Many thanks to Barbara and his team, for this second great course ... I must say that "learning to learn" has been the first MOOC that I have completed and that changed my knowledge, showing me that there was no limitation to continue learning Live miestas (I am 62 years old) and that in addition, my quality of life will be greatly benefited, as far as you continue to learn. The truth is that the acknowledgments are few and poor compared to the change that has been generated in me, thank you these courses .......... I went to Italy for a walk and I was able to communicate in Italian, I went to Russia to see The Confederations Cup and I was able to communicate in Russian, I would never have ever imagined that this could happen, I have made several other MOOCs (cooking in vacuum, preparation of Games via PC, etc.). I write this reference in Spanish, to motivate the Latinage A hug and infinite thanks.

name: Mindshift: Break Through Obstacles to Learning and Discover Your Hidden Potential
reviews: This MOOC could not have arrived at a better time; I am in a stage of changes, not only by the Coronavirus, I want to say at a personal level, I arrived at a turning point, and many of the arguments and knowledge I received through this course have motivated to catch the bull by the horns and fight to be my best version of myself. Thanks for everything! _______________ This MOOC could not arrive at a better time; I am in a stage of changes, not only because of the coronavirus, but at a personal level, I reached a point of inflection, and many of the arguments and knowledge I received through this course, have motivated me to take the bull For the horns and fight for being my best version of myself. Thank you so much for everything!

name: Mindshift: Break Through Obstacles to Learning and Discover Your Hidden Potential
reviews: Excellent course Very useful for those who do not feel able to undertake new adventures of study, or people who want to change their lives, either in the work, as a professional. It gives you new and refreshing points of view about learning, and knocks down many myths about learning, and the ability to learn as we get older. In addition, it has great motivational value. Barbara and her team have done, once again, a great job !! Thanks for everything!!

name: Mindshift: Break Through Obstacles to Learning and Discover Your Hidden Potential
reviews: Excellent course I would have liked to know these techniques, methods and tricks from my youth. I have reinforced my way of thinking, I have always been a self-taught, and these teachings ratify that I have been on the right path. I appreciate the teachers for sharing their knowledge and experiences. Always positive in life and it is good to change mentality to achieve success in everything we undertook. Good luck to you all.

reviews: Very basic, little teaching on lighting, opening and speed issues that is expected in a photo course. Tasks do not leave you great learning.

name: Cameras, Exposure, and Photography
reviews: This was an introductory course that went over the history of photography, the elements of the camera, how to use the camera in program mode, and how to creatively work with the frame among other topics. I found the course too cursory at times and there was not enough opportunity for practice and feedback before getting to the graded assignments. Some content seemed out of logical order. (e.g., Elements of a camera should have come before how to use the camera in program mode .) The quizzes and assignments had instructions that were often badly worded and confusing. e.g., Why were we graded on whether we titled our picture "frame" or "scene"? The last assignment rubric did not allow peer reviewers to select 0 points on the fifth rubric criterion. Overall learning was minor.

name: Cameras, Exposure, and Photography

name: Introducción a Data Science: Programación Estadística con R
reviews: If you are looking for a first approach to L language, this is a course I would recommend - although, with certain reservations. Pros: 1) clear and uncomplicated explanations of syntax, commands, functions, etc.; 2) SWIRL lessons bring their entertainment and interactivity quota; 3) Videos have image and sound of very good quality, which is always something worthy of thanking; 4) The one used by the RSTUDIO environment is an important "plus". Cons (and why I evaluate only 3/5 stars): 1) The title of the course does not correspond to what is transmitted. This course is not an introduction to data science, but an introduction to the programming language R-I suppose they put the "Data Science" net by an advertising issue. 2) The pedagogical strategy is loose. The instructor and SWIRL lessons, except for exceptions, is only limited to exposing the functioning of functions and commands, which simple glossary; That is, nothing that one, with a level of English and minimum programming, can consult in any book and / or online manual. 3) Total absence of practical exercises in which one built codes (or parts of codes). It remains the feeling that everything has to be learned from memory (especially in the last week), being that its own practice is what, definitely, allows you to retain concepts naturally. 4) I rarely use the forums, but those who usually use it can be somewhat discouraging, since there are too many unanswered questions (I imagine need more helpers to maintain the interaction). Despite everything, I consider it a reasonable course, which is worth taking as an introduction.

reviews: This is how all the programming courses should be. It is true that it is a language with lots of functions, some too concrete and specialized, but after doing the course I have realized that there are a number of basic functions with which you can do a lot of things relatively simple, about All in terms of simple mathematical operations, elementary statistical functions and graphic representation. All this, much easier to perform if the RSTUDIO environment is used, which is also someduly explained in this course. Today, with such demand in the Big Data sector, this language has become an essential tool (can that the most fundamental of all) very required in the labor market. name: Python Programming: A Concise Introduction
reviews: A good short introduction to Python programming, which would also work well as a refreshed for someone who hasn't programmed in Python for a while and wanted to brush up on some of the basic syntax. I like the approach used, through using the Spyder integrated environment, and the exercises with extensive notes. Some of the exercises are a little painful in terms of the code we are asked to write, but it does get more 'Pythonic' towards the end of the course. I found the decision to only introduce returning values from functions in the last unit to be rather surprising, and even then it was only done in a very cursory way. On the plus side, I really liked the iterative description of the development of the phone database utility, which tied together everything introduced earlier in the course.The only big issue with this course is that it could really do with being longer, and introducing some more of the key Python modules, together with more of the language features (such as list comprehensions) which people are likely to see in Python code written by others. Overall, though, it fulfils its objective to be a concise introduction to Python, and lays the groundwork for people to go and work through more extensive material elsewhere.

I also think that it would come well a little more than theory and explain how language is structured because in the course it deals quickly in language but not much in how it is structured. name: Introdução à Ciência da Computação com Python Parte 1
reviews: Some points on the course: 1) In fact, it is a course of programming / computational algorithms; 2) The teacher clearly does not dominate language; 3) the teacher's didactics is very weak, not to say non-existent; 4) the Level of activities do not match the classes given. Lucky I was not a beginner in programming logic / computational algorithms; 5) The teacher seemed not to know what he was talking about several times, always "sticking" from some paper / notebook that was on the computer side; 6) the theory of the course It is shallow, not to say non-existent; 7) The final activity does not match the level of the course. Again, lucky that I was not a beginner in programming logic / computational algorithms; 7) is a certificate that is not worth $ 29.00 (R $ 154, 71 at the exchange of 05/05/2020).

name: Introdução à Ciência da Computação com Python Parte 1
reviews: The course teaches in the Python IDdle that is much more difficult to use than a specific program for programming such as Pycharm or Visual Studio Code. Some exercises are complex for an 'Introduction' course. An exercise with almost 100 lines should not be in an introductory course. Classes seem to have not been planned and many errors occur during filming. There are free courses on Youtube who teach more calmly and have a better design.
reviewers: By Caio S A d S

name: Introdução à Ciência da Computação com Python Parte 1
reviews: Without wanting to be malicious, it is the type of course that passes who searches for help out of course because what is charged is far beyond what is taught.
